      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "03e317170d7a4907",
      "text": "salience network"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f1e3beeccc766d13",
      "text": ">The salience network—the anterior insula, anterior cingulate cortex, and ventral striatum—is involved in the interoception of the feelings associated with reward.\n>\nBrain regions comprising the salience network, including dorsal anterior cingulate and anterior insular cortices, are among the most commonly activated across a wide range of tasks. The insula in particular appears to play a critical role in the detection of novel salient stimuli across multiple modalities. Insula activity correlates with subjective salience as modulated by homeostatic, emotional, or cognitive factors. [https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/salience-network source]"
    },
